## Conclusion and Recommendations

The sharing of health data online presents profound ethical challenges that must be addressed to protect individuals and maximize societal benefits. Privacy and confidentiality are paramount, requiring advanced technical safeguards and clear, enforceable policies. Respect for autonomy demands innovative consent models that empower patients without compromising care quality.

Security protocols must evolve to meet the risks posed by big data analytics and interconnected technologies. Equity considerations require deliberate efforts to ensure that digital health advances do not deepen existing disparities.

Finally, maintaining public trust through transparency, engagement, and respect for rights is essential to sustain the social license for health data sharing. Healthcare providers, policymakers, technologists, and ethicists must collaborate to develop frameworks that balance these competing interests responsibly.

